english:
  title: A Song on the Lotus Sutra
  author: Lee Gyou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    [Preface]

    I came to be favored by the Great Master Zhijue of Cheonsu Temple. Whenever I visited his chamber, I would arrive drunk and feign madness, scarcely reading the Buddhist texts. The master said to me: "Your wildness stems from your youth—in time you will surely reflect upon yourself. Yet know that the ancient scholars and gentlemen of old read the Lotus Sutra often, taking it as essential to cultivating the mind. Will you not do the same?" Moved to tears, I listened intently. From that moment, I read without ceasing. When I had read through all eighty-seven thousand five hundred and five characters, I realized it was truly the vast gateway through which all sentient beings enter the One Vehicle. I then pledged to my master: "Within three days, I shall recite two scrolls." The master did not believe me. After three days had passed, I came to his chamber and, reciting from memory with my back to the text, had scarcely finished the first fascicle when the master lit incense, sat upright, and listened, saying: "I, this old monk, have devoted myself to this sutra since youth, yet have never memorized even one scroll or one chapter. How swift your progress! Surely this is the fruit of practice from past lives." He then expounded upon the great principles of Cessation and Contemplation, guiding me broadly in their meaning. Thus I glimpsed something of the truth. Retiring, I composed this song on the Lotus Sutra to present to him:

    Because sentient beings wander in delusion,
    The Buddha uses provisional teachings and metaphors to guide them to true nature.
    Three paths converge into one—that principle knows no bounds,
    Beyond the dualistic gate, transcending all the saints.

    As when the sun reaches the zenith of heaven,
    At midday no shadow can be cast.
    At that moment gods and men listen with clear attention,
    Sixty small eons pass like a single meal.

    Alas, the three realms are worn thin by suffering,
    All beings play within that burning house.
    First the Buddha coaxes them out with ox-drawn carts,
    Then bestows upon them carriages adorned with seven treasures.

    If one merely reads the words but grasps not their meaning,
    Mind remains mind and tongue remains tongue.
    Only when tongue is no tongue and mind is no mind,
    Does one attain true extinction and peace.

    I, a disciple and lay practitioner named Chun-gyeong, bow in reverence
    Before the Wondrous Law Lotus Sutra.
    Through countless eons and births, may I uphold and preserve it—
    Perchance I shall see a blue lotus bloom upon my tongue.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'burning house' (火宅) is a famous parable from the Lotus Sutra, where the world of suffering is compared to a house engulfed in flames, from which the Buddha entices all beings to escape.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'seven treasures' (七寶) refer to the precious rewards given to those who follow the Buddha's teachings, symbolizing the supreme benefit of enlightenment.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'blue lotus' (靑蓮) is a traditional Buddhist symbol of enlightenment and spiritual attainment, suggesting the speaker's aspiration to achieve Buddhahood through faithful practice.
